Don't store local state across calls like this; it limits our ability to e.g. recover from a failed engine in the future. Any shared state must be returned from handle_create() (and will then be passed as the input parameter to check_create_complete()).

However, in this case you can just use:

  if not self.properties[self.ACTIVE]:

My point was that active is None and active is True are the same case.

The case that should be treated differently is

  if active is False:

The only case that actually matters here is

  if active is True:

since the False case is already handled in handle_update().

